# What is Mobile-First Design?

Mobile-first is a CSS strategy where you write your base styles for the **smallest screen** first, then use media queries with `min-width` to enhance the design for larger screens.

This is the opposite of what many beginners do naturally (design for desktop, then try to fix mobile).

## Desktop-First vs Mobile-First

**Desktop-first** (starts big, breaks down):
```css
/* Default — desktop styles */
.card { flex: 0 0 calc(33% - 11px); }

/* Override for mobile */
@media (max-width: 480px) {
  .card { flex: 0 0 100%; }
}
```

**Mobile-first** (starts small, scales up):
```css
/* Default — mobile styles */
.card { flex: 0 0 100%; }

/* Tablet and above */
@media (min-width: 640px) {
  .card { flex: 0 0 calc(50% - 8px); }
}

/* Desktop and above */
@media (min-width: 1024px) {
  .card { flex: 0 0 calc(33% - 11px); }
}
```

## Why Mobile-First?

- Mobile users are the majority — start with their experience
- Simpler CSS — mobile layouts are naturally simpler; you add complexity for larger screens
- Better performance — mobile devices download the base CSS first; media queries for desktop only trigger on larger screens
- Forces good decisions — if your content makes sense on mobile, it works everywhere

## Practical Rules for Mobile-First

1. **Stack everything vertically by default** — `flex-direction: column` or block elements
2. **Use full widths by default** — `width: 100%` on cards and inputs
3. **Set comfortable font sizes** — `font-size: 16px` minimum to prevent zoom-in on iOS
4. **Make tap targets large** — buttons and links at least `44px` tall
5. **Add desktop enhancements with min-width** — multi-column layouts, larger headings

## Responsive Units

| Unit | Description |
|---|---|
| `px` | Fixed pixels — not responsive |
| `%` | Relative to parent element |
| `em` | Relative to parent font-size |
| `rem` | Relative to root font-size (usually 16px) |
| `vw` | 1% of viewport width |
| `vh` | 1% of viewport height |
| `clamp(min, val, max)` | Fluid value between min and max |

